    <!-- NAV Erosion Analysis -->
    <section>
      <h2>NAV Erosion & Return of Capital Analysis</h2>
      <p>Understanding ULTY requires grasping the concept of <strong>return of capital (ROC)</strong>. With a payout ratio of 7,003%, the vast majority of distributions aren't true income - they're your own investment being returned to you while the share price declines.</p>

      <div class="analysis-card">
        <h3>The ROC Reality</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Payout Ratio:</strong> 7,003% means paying out 70x more than earnings</li>
          <li><strong>Source of Distributions:</strong> Primarily option premiums + liquidating assets</li>
          <li><strong>Tax Impact:</strong> ROC reduces cost basis, potentially creating larger capital gains later</li>
          <li><strong>NAV Decay:</strong> Share price erosion typically exceeds distribution income over time</li>
        </ul>
        
        <div class="example-box">
          <h4>Example Scenario:</h4>
          <p>Buy 100 shares at $30 = $3,000 investment<br>
          Receive $40.20/share annually = $4,020 income<br>
          Share price drops to $20 by year-end<br>
          <strong>Net result:</strong> +$4,020 cash, -$1,000 value = $3,020 gain (0.67% return)</p>
        </div>
