    <!-- FAQ Section -->
    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What is ULTY dividend history?</summary>
        <p>ULTY dividend history shows a dramatic decline from $8-10 monthly distributions in 2024 to $0.40-0.50 weekly distributions in 2026. The YieldMax Ultra Option Income Strategy ETF started with massive payouts but has experienced significant NAV erosion and declining distributions as market volatility patterns shifted and the fund's assets were depleted through excessive distributions.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How much is the current ULTY dividend?</summary>
        <p>The current ULTY dividend is $0.432 per share weekly (as of March 25, 2026), yielding 134.01% annually at the current $30 share price. This translates to approximately $22.46 in annualized income per share, though the distribution amount fluctuates based on market volatility and option premiums collected by the fund.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Why is ULTY yield so high at 134%?</summary>
        <p>ULTY's 134% yield is artificially high due to a 7,003% payout ratio, meaning the fund pays out far more than it earns. Most distributions are return of capital rather than actual income, effectively returning investors' own money while the share price declines. This creates the illusion of massive income while eroding principal.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Is ULTY dividend sustainable long-term?</summary>
        <p>No, ULTY dividend is not sustainable long-term. The extreme payout ratio of 7,003% indicates distributions far exceed earnings, requiring constant liquidation of assets to fund payments. The distribution decline from $8-10 monthly to $0.43 weekly demonstrates this unsustainability, and continued NAV erosion will eventually force further distribution cuts.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How does ULTY compare to MSTY?</summary>
        <p>ULTY vs MSTY: ULTY uses a multi-asset covered call strategy on various volatile stocks with 134% current yield, while MSTY focuses specifically on Microsoft with 50-60% yield. ULTY offers higher current income but faces greater NAV decay risk due to its broader volatility exposure and higher distribution rate.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What is ULTY's payout ratio and what does it mean?</summary>
        <p>ULTY's payout ratio is 7,003%, meaning the fund pays out 70 times more than it earns. This extreme ratio indicates that distributions consist primarily of return of capital - essentially giving investors their own money back while the underlying share value declines. It's a red flag for unsustainable income generation.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How often does ULTY pay dividends?</summary>
        <p>ULTY pays dividends weekly as of 2026, transitioning from monthly payments in 2024-2025. While the frequency increased, the total amount per distribution decreased significantly. Weekly payments provide more consistent cash flow but at much lower per-payment amounts compared to the historic monthly distributions.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What causes ULTY distribution amounts to vary?</summary>
        <p>ULTY distribution amounts vary based on market volatility and option premiums collected. When underlying stocks experience high volatility, call options become more expensive, allowing the fund to collect higher premiums. During calm market periods, option premiums decline, reducing distributable income and forcing lower payouts or asset liquidation.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
